Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, which is supported by individual and collective successes in sport, the arts, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for secondary and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a special school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will reach his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust people in other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest promotion rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained a Higher A grade certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students obtained a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; also 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish obtained such a certificate.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, as a subject, are held in the same place as STEM subjects in independent school curricula and other fields.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that of the reasons employers gave for struggling to fill vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming imperative in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities that require foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having this skill throughout their life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in foreign language learning is important for today's children.
Having more languages, especially in developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, every school will teach another foreign language.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be most important for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be more languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and empower children with the skills to succeed, whatever the future.
It cannot be denied at this moment, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
It must be done well .
