A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to get more sleep in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture that causes them to undergo "all-night" study sessions, energized by high caffeine.
One researcher found that students at the world's most prestigious university often do not even have a basic understanding of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning ability.
And at the end, this girl came up to me and said, "Why are you telling me this now, last year?"
She told me she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students the key concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall wellbeing.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a series of interactive tasks.
A section shows a picture of a dorm room, and students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, sweatpants and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a sleep schedule.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
We know we can't instantly change student behavior.
