One of the grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "wonderfully symbolic" that the stone would be unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather won the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Saint-Quentin Canal "in very thick fog and under heavy artillery and machine gun fire".
Later, he rushed to the front line and, with "fantastic bravery", cleared the way for the soldiers, then single-handedly attacked an artillery nest and managed to eliminate three of the detachment's weapons.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "something I know I'll never be able to match, but it makes me feel humbled".
He, along with his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade, which was conducted by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Orchestra.
Michael Vann said that he "feels very honoured to play a role in the parade" and added that "the value of a true hero is demonstrated by the support he gets from a lot of people".
MMA fans stayed up all night to see Bellator 206, but got Peppa Pig cartoons instead.
Imagine you've been up all night watching Bellator 206, a multi-star event, only to miss the main event.
The San Jose event schedule contained 13 fights, including six on the main panel, and was to be broadcast live all night in the UK on Channel 5.
At 6am, just as Gegard Mousasi was preparing to face Rory MacDonald, viewers in the UK were stunned when the broadcast was replaced with an episode of Peppa Pig.
Some were not satisfied at all, because they stayed up all night to watch the fight.
One fan described the switch to children's cartoons on Twitter as "some kind of bad joke".
"Government regulations say this content is not suitable for 6am, so they had to switch to children's programming", said Dave Schwartz, Bellator's senior vice president of marketing and communications, when asked about the broadcast.
Peppa Pig, yeah.
Scott Coker, president of Bellator, said that in the future they will schedule their events in a way that they can be watched by viewers in the UK.
"When I think about re-shoots, I think we could probably work it out", Coker said.
But it's six in the morning on a Sunday here and we won't be able to do it until Sunday, our time, or Monday, their time.
But we're working on it.
Believe me, when the schedule changed, I started getting a lot of text messages and they weren't all friendly.
We tried to resolve the situation, we thought it was a technical glitch.
But it wasn't that. It was a government regulation.
I can promise you it won't happen again next time.
We're going to be down to five fights instead of six, as we usually do, and we tried to give the fans more, and we overstepped the mark.
It's an unfortunate situation.
Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality.
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone because of his sexuality, but that's what motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old athlete said he didn't realize until he got to school that "not everyone is like me".
A guest on the first Desert Island Discs show hosted by Lauren Laverne on Radio 4, he said he talks about gay rights to give others "hope".
The athlete also said that when he became a parent, he cared less about the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of the traditional show, will be out for a few months due to illness.
Invited to the first edition presented by Laverne, Daley said that as a child he felt "inferior" to others because "it was not socially acceptable for me to like both boys and girls".
He said, "So far, these feelings of inferiority and feeling different, they've been the real things that have given me the strength and resilience to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was "somebody", he said, so he wouldn't disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent supporter of LGBT campaigns and used an appearance at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he decided to speak out because he felt lucky to be able to live freely, without consequences, and because he wanted to give others hope.
The three-time world champion said he was taken by surprise when he fell in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black.
Daley married the Oscar-winning filmmaker last year, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never an issue.
"When you go through so much at such a young age" - he participated in his first Olympics when he was only 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said, "it's hard to find someone your age who has gone through the same ups and downs".
The couple became parents in June to a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, which, Daley says, changed "his whole perspective".
"If I had been asked last year, I would have been interested in nothing but winning a gold medal", he said.
You know, there are things more important than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.
His son is named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said that his father couldn't accept that he was going to die and that one of the last things he wanted to do was find out if they had gotten tickets to the 2012 London Olympics because he wanted to be first.
"I couldn't tell him you couldn't be the first, Dad", he said.
"I held his hand when he stopped breathing, and it was only after he stopped breathing and died that I finally accepted that he was not invincible", he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
"I knew that this was what I had dreamed of all my life, to jump in front of my country's spectators at the Olympics, there is no greater feeling", he said.
This also inspired him in his chosen music, Proud by Heather Small, a song that encouraged him before the Olympics and still moves him.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays at 11:15.
Mickelson, out of form, was put on the bench for Saturday's Ryder Cup
American Phil Mickelson will set a record on Saturday when he plays in his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he'll have to get back in shape to make sure it's not an unfortunate occasion.
Mickelson, who is playing in the biennial event for the twelfth time, another record, was passed over on the bench by captain Jim Furyk for Saturday's fourballs and foursome trials.
Instead of being the center of the action, as he has often been for the U.S. team, the five-time major championship winner has split his day between cheering for teammates and practicing his shots, hoping to right what went wrong.
The 48-year-old has never had the most straight drives, even in the prime of his career, so he's not the best choice for the tight court at Le Golf National, where long rough patches often punish incorrect shots.
And if the field isn't a big enough challenge, in Sunday's ninth game Mickelson will face Francesco Molinari, the meticulous British Open champion who teamed up with rookie Tommy Fleetwood to win all four matches of the week.
Mickelson's match could prove absolutely crucial for the Americans, who are four points clear of the 12-game playoff, which is set to begin in force at this stage.
Furyk declared himself confident in his player's ability, but he couldn't have said otherwise anyway.
"He fully understood the role he had today, he patted me on the shoulder, hugged me and told me he would be ready for tomorrow", Furyk said.
He's very confident in himself.
He's a member of the Hall of Fame and he's contributed a lot to these teams in the past and this week.
I probably didn't imagine he'd play in two games.
I imagined more, but this is what happened and this is how I thought we should proceed.
He wants to play, like everyone else.
On Sunday, Mickelson will beat Nick Faldo's record for most Ryder Cup games played.
This could be the end of his Ryder Cup career, which never rose to his personal best.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven halves, although Furyk has stated that his presence has brought some intangible benefits to the team.
"He's funny, he's sarcastic, he's smart, he likes to joke with the players, he's a great guy in the team locker room", he explained.
I think the young players are having fun playing with him, it was fun to watch them do that during the week.
His role is more important, it's not just about the game.
Europe's captain, Thomas Bjorn, knows that considerable lead could soon be gone
Thomas Bjorn, the European captain, knows from experience that the considerable lead held before the first day of singles in the Ryder Cup can easily turn into an uncomfortable journey.
The Dane made his debut in the 1997 match at Valderrama, when the team led by captain Seve Ballesteros led the Americans by five points, but barely managed to beat them by a bare minimum of 141⁄2 to 131⁄2.
