Tomorrow we have to play at maximum speed.
Let's get out on the field and make everything perfect.
The game is not over until the points are passed to the table.
We have a goal and that is to win this trophy, that must remain the goal.
We always say, we have to focus on the 12 players on our team, but we also know what's waiting for us on the other side: the best players in the world.
Pleased with how his players handled themselves on a difficult pitch, Bjorn added: 'I'm not rushing to conclusions.
Tomorrow is a whole different situation.
Tomorrow's all about individual performance, and this is different.
It's great to be on the court with a partner when things are going well, but when you're on your own, that's when you're tested the most, as a golfer.
That's the message you have to send to the players, that they have to be at their best tomorrow.
Now they leave their partner behind and have to play as best they can.
Unlike Bjorn, Jim Furyk, the opposing team's captain, hopes his players will play better in the singles event than they did with their partners, with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who won three of four points.
Furyk himself was on both sides of such comebacks on the final day: he was on the winning team at Brookline, then on the losing team when Europe achieved the "miracle at Medina".
