Germany's new warship, delayed again
The newest frigate of the German Navy was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the outdated warships of the Cold War, but this will not happen until next year, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigate, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The vessel was due to be commissioned in 2014, but problems after delivery affected this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the older Bremen-class frigates.
It is assumed that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and stealth technologies, which provide a low radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Other important features will include longer maintenance periods; it should be possible for new frigates to be able to go on missions of up to two years without returning to their original port.
However, the continuing delays mean that these state-of-the-art warships, which are said to boost Germany's naval strength, will already be obsolete before they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated frigate F125 was discussed in the press last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Not much information is available on the reasons for the refusal, but the German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware flaws" that would have made the warship useless in a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half the crews of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship proved to be overweight, which reduced her performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future equipment.
The 7,000-tonne ship Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as the ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty mechanisms, the cost of the entire project, including the training of the crew, became a concern.
It is said to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), up from the original price of 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of the newest frigates are of particular importance given the latest warnings that Germany's naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, acknowledged that the navy was "beginning to run out of ships that can be sent on missions".
The official said the problem had steadily increased over time as old vessels were taken out of service without being replaced with new ones.
It regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates had entered service with the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use their environment to hunt prey.
It is hoped that the discoveries will reveal new things about the behavior of these unusual flying mammals and help future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will look at common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as eared bats and water bats from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also carry out mobile studies using handheld detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and which species emit particular sounds.
A habitat map and a report will also be produced to create a detailed, scale-up picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating grassland, and which is the best way to maintain forest grasslands for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout Britain have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects their nests, but also by habitat loss.
And wind turbines and street lighting are risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also domestic cat attacks.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to accurately identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks, and 76,000 acres of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, inspect nests, and sometimes conduct rescue missions.
The organisation even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve, on the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten bat species are found.
The property manager, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here at Threave, the area is wonderful for bats", he says.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us understand what they need to reproduce.
It stresses the importance of looking for bats before carrying out maintenance work on properties, as the mere unintentional destruction of a mother's nest could kill up to 400 females and chicks, which could wipe out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and killing, harassing or disturbing them, and destroying their nests, are prohibited.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and we don't know how populations evolve for many of our species".
Ronaldo denies rape charges as lawyers prepare to sue German magazine
