Brexit: Britain would forever regret the loss of carmakers
Britain would forever regret losing its status as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit, Business Secretary Greg Clark said.
He added that it was 'worrying' that Toyota UK told the BBC that if the UK left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at its Burnaston plant near Derby.
"We need an agreement", Clark said.
The Japanese carmaker said that the impact of border delays in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, where Toyota's Auris and Avensis brands are manufactured, produced almost 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
'My view is that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our plant,' said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's chief executive at Burnaston.
Other UK carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have said they fear leaving the EU without a deal on cross-border trade.
BMW, for example, says that after Brexit, it will close the Oxford plant where the Mini is produced for a month.
The main concerns are created by what producers call supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line operates on the 'fix-it-time' principle: for custom-made cars, parts arrive at 37-minute intervals from suppliers in the UK and EU.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be problems at the border, which industrial manufacturers say could cause delays and a shortage of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to store more than a day's worth of inventory at its Derbyshire plant, the company says, so production would be halted.
Clark said Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is "precisely calibrated to avoid these border delays".
"We want to have the best deal that will allow us not only to enjoy the success we have now but also to take advantage of this opportunity", he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
Evidence from not only Toyota but also other manufacturers shows that we need to be able to continue to use what has been a very successful set of supply chains.
Toyota could not say how long production would have to stop, but warned that increased prices could reduce the factory's competitiveness in the long run and ultimately lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at Burnaston for 24 years and is the head of the United Union at the factory, said members were increasingly worried: "My experience has been that once these jobs disappear, they don't come back".
A government spokesman said: We have created a clear and credible plan for the future relationship with the EU.
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be postponed again, says White House
Donald Trump's high-level meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be "postponed for another week" as the fight for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian election interference, ties between Trump aides and Russia, and potential obstruction of justice by the president.
Rumors of Trump firing the assistant attorney general, thus jeopardizing Mueller's independence, have been circulating in Washington circles for months.
Earlier this month, The New York Times reported that Rosenstein discussed the possibility of wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of suspending the president via the 25th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.
Rosenstein denied that report.
But last Monday he went to the White House, and reports claim he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting was announced for Thursday with Trump, who was then at the United Nations in New York.
Trump stated that he would prefer not to fire Rosenstein, but then the meeting was postponed to avoid a conflict with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing, in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual misconduct, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, testified.
On Friday, Trump called for a week-long FBI investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh, which again delayed the Senate vote.
Trump's press secretary, Sarah Sanders, appeared on Fox News on Sunday.
Asked about the Rosenstein meeting, she said, "It's not set yet, it could be this week or it could be postponed by a week, given all the other things going on at the Supreme Court.
But we'll see, and I always like to keep the press informed.
Some reporters would dispute this claim: Sanders has not had a press briefing at the White House since September 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders claimed that the reduction in briefings was not due to antipathy towards TV reporters, who like to show off, though he added: "I don't deny that they like to show off".
Then he suggested that there would be increased direct contact between Trump and the press.
The President attends more question and answer sessions than all previous presidents, she said, adding without citing any evidence: I have looked at the figures.
"There will be more briefings", Sanders said, "but I think it's much better that the press has the opportunity to ask questions directly to the president of the United States, not to me".
We try to do this most of the time, and you can see that we've done this a lot in the last few weeks, and the talks with the president of the United States will replace the press briefings when they're available.
Trump usually answers questions when he leaves the White House or when he attends open sessions or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
