Foreign buyers will be charged a higher court stamp fee when buying property in the UK
Foreign buyers will pay a higher court stamp duty when buying property in the UK, with the extra money to be used to help homeless people under new Conservative Party plans
This change will neutralize the success of Corbyn's efforts to attract young voters.
The court stamp duty will be applied to persons who are not taxpayers in the United Kingdom
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year to help homeless people
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher rate of court stamp duty when buying property in the UK, and the extra money will be used to help homeless people, Theresa May is due to announce today.
The change will be seen as an attempt to offset the success of Jeremy Corbyn's efforts to attract young voters by promising homes at lower prices and targeting high-income earners.
The higher court stamp fee will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not tax payers in the United Kingdom and the additional money thus raised will be used to support the Government's efforts to help homeless people.
The surcharge, which is added to the current court stamp duty, including the high levels of two years ago for second property and properties bought for rental, could reach 3%.
The Treasury expects this change to bring in an extra up to £120 million a year.
Approximately 13% of newly built properties in London are bought by non-UK residents, which leads to higher prices and makes it difficult for those looking to buy their first home.
Several prosperous areas of the country, especially the capital, have become "ghost towns" because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend much of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in the court stamp duty to help young people buy their first home.
It accused large construction firms of keeping property prices high by buying land without using it and asked Theresa May to drop taxes on affordable houses in order to solve the UK's 'housing problem'.
Corbyn announced a number of attractive proposals for housing reforms, including rent controls and an end to unjustified evictions.
It also wants to give councils greater powers in terms of building new homes.
Theresa May said the following: Last year I said that I would devote my term as Prime Minister to fulfilling the British dream, a better life for each new generation.
And that means fixing the problems that exist in the real estate market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it is not fair that non-UK residents, as well as companies based abroad, can buy homes as easily as hardworking UK residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home has become far too remote, and living in undignified conditions is far too real.
