In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some key facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, which is located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of Sulawesi Island with a population of approximately 379,800 inhabitants in 2017.
The city was celebrating 40 years of existence when it was hit by the tsunami and earthquake.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along a coastline of over 300 km in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, an administrative region that is located at the bottom of a province, has a population of approximately 299,200 inhabitants in 2017.
Fish farming and agriculture are the core of the economy of the Central Sulawesi Province, especially the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining activities are also important in the province but are mainly concentrated in Morowali on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Also in 1996, a tsunami hit the western part of Donggala Regency, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Ring of Fire, an area of intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004: On 26 December, a powerful earthquake off the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province, north of Sumatra island, triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale struck the south of Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake measuring 7.6 on the Richter scale struck near the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake measuring 7.5 on the Richter scale struck one of the Mentawai Islands off the coast of Sumatra, triggering a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A low-intensity earthquake struck Aceh's Pidie Jaya Regency, causing damage and panic as people recalled the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami that resulted in a large number of deaths.
This time no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people died because of collapsed buildings.
2018: Several strong earthquakes occurred on the tourist island of Lombok, killing over 500 people, mostly in the northern part of the island.
