Red tide news: concentrations have decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations for certain areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties  suggesting decreasing concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over an area of coastline of about 130 miles [210 km], from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 10 miles off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations found in or around Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations in Manatee County, low to high concentrations in Sarasota County or around Sarasota County, low to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, low to high concentrations in Lee County and around Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reported cases of respiratory irritation in northwest Florida in the past week.
